[SPEAKER_08]: So again,

185
00:19:40,733 --> 00:19:49,676
[SPEAKER_08]: We have a lot bigger things on our plate that we should be doing than worrying about spending, we spent a lot of money on the right of an ordinance that we were doing okay with in the past.

186
00:19:49,696 --> 00:19:59,659
[SPEAKER_08]: So I just don't know, I just don't see the quick need to get this done this quick when there's very little call for food trucks in this community.

187
00:20:02,260 --> 00:20:03,020
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you, Councilor Carvillo.

188
00:20:03,060 --> 00:20:03,620
[SPEAKER_04]: Vice President Behrs.

189
00:20:04,757 --> 00:20:05,758
[SPEAKER_00]: Thank you, Madam President.

190
00:20:05,838 --> 00:20:11,923
[SPEAKER_00]: I mean, I think mass noncompliance with the existing policy is an indication that we should update the policy.

191
00:20:11,943 --> 00:20:14,545
[SPEAKER_00]: I have specific questions.

192
00:20:15,886 --> 00:20:21,811
[SPEAKER_00]: First being, in the current process, Victor, do we require reports from police, fire, and engineering?

193
00:20:24,593 --> 00:20:26,215
[SPEAKER_02]: We don't, no.

194
00:20:27,156 --> 00:20:33,181
[SPEAKER_02]: The way we've been operating is when a food truck would like to come into the community for

195
00:20:34,918 --> 00:20:52,372
[SPEAKER_02]: for an event, they will submit essentially a summary of the event and to our office, PDS, and through the mayor's office, we'll present that to council for consideration.

196
00:20:54,293 --> 00:20:57,335
[SPEAKER_00]: And do we currently require a quarry check or a background check?

197
00:20:59,897 --> 00:21:01,459
[SPEAKER_02]: I do not believe so, no.

198
00:21:02,579 --> 00:21:02,980
[SPEAKER_00]: Okay.

199
00:21:04,313 --> 00:21:23,310
[SPEAKER_00]: I would be comfortable amending those two sections to, you know, instead of speaking at an official report, have the board of health coordinate with police, fire and engineering to address any issues that stand out to those departments within the application.

200
00:21:26,313 --> 00:21:27,194
[SPEAKER_00]: And that's a motion.

201
00:21:32,592 --> 00:21:36,495
[SPEAKER_04]: Could you repeat that, Vice President Behrs, or if you haven't written it?

202
00:21:36,515 --> 00:21:38,516
[SPEAKER_00]: It's a motion, I don't have it written.

203
00:21:38,937 --> 00:22:02,354
[SPEAKER_00]: It's a motion that instead of whatever the section is requiring reports from police, fire, and engineering, and the CORI check, that the Board of Health coordinate with the police department, fire department, and engineering department to highlight any issues that those departments see with an application, with any application.

204
00:22:26,628 --> 00:22:30,670
[SPEAKER_04]: So on the motion of Vice President Behrs is seconded by Councilor Collins.

205
00:22:31,451 --> 00:22:32,351
[SPEAKER_04]: Mr. Clerk, please call the roll.

206
00:22:36,497 --> 00:22:36,757
[SPEAKER_05]: Yes.

207
00:22:38,218 --> 00:22:38,818
[SPEAKER_06]: Councilor Kerrio.

208
00:22:38,838 --> 00:22:38,998
[SPEAKER_06]: Yes.

209
00:22:40,319 --> 00:22:40,839
[SPEAKER_06]: Councilor Collins.

210
00:22:41,019 --> 00:22:41,199
[SPEAKER_05]: Yes.

211
00:22:41,939 --> 00:22:42,820
[SPEAKER_06]: Councilor Nunes is absent.

212
00:22:43,720 --> 00:22:44,220
[SPEAKER_06]: Councilor Scarpello.

213
00:22:44,240 --> 00:22:44,340
[SPEAKER_06]: No.

214
00:22:48,462 --> 00:22:48,842
[SPEAKER_06]: Councilor Sang.

215
00:22:48,862 --> 00:22:48,942
[SPEAKER_06]: Yes.

216
00:22:50,142 --> 00:22:50,623
[SPEAKER_06]: Councilor Morrell.

217
00:22:51,183 --> 00:22:51,383
[SPEAKER_04]: Yes.

218
00:22:51,743 --> 00:22:55,985
[SPEAKER_04]: Five in the affirmative, one present, one absent, zero in the negative.

219
00:22:56,585 --> 00:22:57,245
[SPEAKER_04]: Motion passes.

220
00:22:58,666 --> 00:23:00,307
[SPEAKER_04]: Any other questions from councilors at this time?

221
00:23:01,607 --> 00:23:03,348
[SPEAKER_04]: I do have one question, Victor.

222
00:23:05,114 --> 00:23:10,779
[SPEAKER_04]: I forget what section we were scrolling through, but where it mentioned that the permit can be longer than one day, but not longer than the event itself.

223
00:23:10,980 --> 00:23:18,446
[SPEAKER_04]: I would assume that this is for, and I do not believe Medford has this, but like, you know, a fair or something that is in town for multiple days in a row.

224
00:23:18,506 --> 00:23:19,547
[SPEAKER_04]: Is that the thought there?

225
00:23:21,589 --> 00:23:22,049
[SPEAKER_02]: Exactly.

226
00:23:22,069 --> 00:23:27,534
[SPEAKER_02]: Yeah, if there was an event, a three-day event, long weekend.

227
00:23:30,237 --> 00:23:30,517
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you.

228
00:23:31,391 --> 00:23:46,222
[SPEAKER_04]: And then, yeah, I just wanna know, I know I get emails every year, the same people email me every year saying, I can't remember how to apply for a food truck permit, I have to go find the word document on the website, then that goes to the mayor, and it becomes like a circular who presents this on the agenda.

229
00:23:46,242 --> 00:23:55,689
[SPEAKER_04]: So I think it's just streamlining and operate, the hope, as I understand, is to streamline and operationalize this process, so it's a bit less onerous for those folks who are applying.

230
00:23:55,749 --> 00:23:59,091
[SPEAKER_04]: And this is something that I, that was actually the last council session,

231
00:24:00,309 --> 00:24:05,323
[SPEAKER_04]: that it was one of the council priorities that we talked about just because it has been a sitting paper for so long.

232
00:24:07,271 --> 00:24:08,492
[SPEAKER_04]: Councilor Sang, did you have?

233
00:24:08,812 --> 00:24:28,265
[SPEAKER_01]: Yeah, and so I've also heard, gotten some emails along those lines, and I wanted to also note that I've heard from residents, maybe this is just, it could be a specific subset of the population that's kind of asking where a city is on food trucks versus other cities.

234
00:24:28,845 --> 00:24:32,207
[SPEAKER_01]: They wanna see more food trucks at fence and stuff like that.

235
00:24:32,287 --> 00:24:36,130
[SPEAKER_01]: And so I have heard, even during the last election,

236
00:24:36,911 --> 00:24:40,434
[SPEAKER_01]: people ask, you know, where, where the winner the updates coming.

237
00:24:41,796 --> 00:24:51,406
[SPEAKER_01]: And as you've noted it's been a city paper for so long and I think a lot of residents, a decent number of residents have been clamoring for action, which I think is important to note.

238
00:24:52,066 --> 00:24:54,889
[SPEAKER_01]: And also I think the point about non compliance that's

239
00:24:56,250 --> 00:25:00,232
[SPEAKER_01]: vice president Ferris, but it's really important because, you know, that hurts restaurants as well.

240
00:25:00,472 --> 00:25:03,593
[SPEAKER_01]: It hurts businesses when we don't go through a proper procedure.

241
00:25:03,854 --> 00:25:14,858
[SPEAKER_01]: And so right now we're kind of stuck in the limbo where perhaps food trucks, you know, aren't benefiting from this complicated process, but we're also hurting restaurants as well.

242
00:25:15,879 --> 00:25:16,159
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you.

243
00:25:16,939 --> 00:25:19,020
[SPEAKER_04]: Vice President Ferris, is your hand up again or still?

244
00:25:22,937 --> 00:25:24,017
[SPEAKER_00]: Still, my apologies.

245
00:25:24,037 --> 00:25:25,978
[SPEAKER_04]: No worries.

246
00:25:26,618 --> 00:25:27,618
[SPEAKER_09]: Madam President, if I can.

247
00:25:28,159 --> 00:25:28,799
[SPEAKER_04]: Councilor Scarpalli.

248
00:25:29,079 --> 00:25:35,701
[SPEAKER_09]: In all the years that I've done this, I think I recall one food truck that's based here in Medford, and they're gone now.

249
00:25:36,581 --> 00:25:38,762
[SPEAKER_09]: So I've been doing this for a long time.

250
00:25:39,982 --> 00:25:49,125
[SPEAKER_09]: We've had one food truck that tried to rob our most needy community by increasing a grilled cheese by 200%.

251
00:25:49,165 --> 00:25:49,665
[SPEAKER_09]: And then,

252
00:25:52,846 --> 00:25:59,528
[SPEAKER_09]: every other came from the main office, the mayor's office, for our approval, which hasn't been daunting at all, I don't believe.

253
00:26:00,148 --> 00:26:20,555
[SPEAKER_09]: So again, it's the brick and mortar, that was what the protection was from the beginning, and that's what we were doing, this council, because of the, especially during the pandemic, what the concerns were, and the hurdles that our brick and mortar establishments were going through.

254
00:26:23,661 --> 00:26:26,462
[SPEAKER_09]: Again, like I said, I've been in this community a long time.

255
00:26:28,523 --> 00:26:37,747
[SPEAKER_09]: I haven't heard one person come to me to talk to me about this ordinance that hasn't been completed because there's never been a hurdle to get a one day permit.

256
00:26:37,787 --> 00:26:38,768
[SPEAKER_09]: There's never been an issue.

257
00:26:39,208 --> 00:26:39,688
[SPEAKER_09]: So thank you.

258
00:26:41,289 --> 00:26:41,949
[SPEAKER_04]: Councilor Kerrio.

259
00:26:42,409 --> 00:26:43,470
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you, Madam President.

260
00:26:43,810 --> 00:26:47,191
[SPEAKER_08]: For people who don't know about the food truck business, I've talked to many people who have food trucks

261
00:26:49,234 --> 00:26:51,258
[SPEAKER_08]: The problem with food trucks is they need people.

262
00:26:52,060 --> 00:26:57,911
[SPEAKER_08]: The reason food trucks don't come here, they don't park here, they don't look to come here is because they can't make money on 50, 60, 70, 100 people.

263
00:27:00,439 --> 00:27:10,127
[SPEAKER_08]: There's the, we don't have a business district where if they want the park, but most of the events that we have don't draw that kind of crowds.

264
00:27:10,187 --> 00:27:22,697
[SPEAKER_08]: I mean, other than maybe the festival of the book school has several people, but most of the events that we have don't draw enough for a property for these vendors to stop the truck and make money.

265
00:27:22,717 --> 00:27:24,219
[SPEAKER_08]: They have to come down here with two or three people

266
00:27:25,215 --> 00:27:27,437
[SPEAKER_08]: pay whatever they have to pay, and they don't make any money.

267
00:27:27,557 --> 00:27:43,289
[SPEAKER_08]: Like I said over the years, we've done, we've approved many food trucks for one day licenses, and they don't show up because they know the kind of crowd that it's like so I don't know who's making these calls to all these people are with the clamoring for these food trucks because food truck people aren't clamoring to come in here.

268
00:27:48,154 --> 00:27:49,094
[SPEAKER_03]: Thank you, President Morrell.

269
00:27:49,334 --> 00:28:04,299
[SPEAKER_03]: And Vic, I was hoping, and I mentioned during your presentation that there were a couple aspects of the ordinance that we were still waiting for outstanding feedback from city departments like Board of Health on promulgating, getting their feedback on the fee structure and promulgating additional requirements for permitting.

270
00:28:04,339 --> 00:28:14,063
[SPEAKER_03]: I was just hoping if you could just revisit kind of the next steps as they pertain to the feedback you're still trying to get from city staff for continuing to finesse this draft.

271
00:28:14,303 --> 00:28:14,563
[SPEAKER_03]: Thank you.

272
00:28:18,823 --> 00:28:20,465
[SPEAKER_02]: Yeah, absolutely counselor.

273
00:28:22,086 --> 00:28:38,942
[SPEAKER_02]: There are some things that I think we need to talk internally about with with health as they'll be overseeing this ordinance and not the ordinance but the, you know, the establishment of the process and approval of licenses.

274
00:28:41,688 --> 00:28:49,253
[SPEAKER_02]: It's, I think we're largely in agreement with internally at the staff level with how this has been developed.

275
00:28:49,313 --> 00:28:51,855
[SPEAKER_02]: It's just language at this point.

276
00:28:51,935 --> 00:29:05,103
[SPEAKER_02]: And there's one concern by the health department about their ability to regulate events on private property.

277
00:29:05,904 --> 00:29:10,487
[SPEAKER_02]: And I think it's pretty clear how this will operate, these ordinance will operate.

278
00:29:12,199 --> 00:29:30,331
[SPEAKER_02]: public property in the right of way, but if someone wants to have a food truck on private property, we just wanna make sure that the ordinance is clear about the health department's oversight and authority.

279
00:29:32,352 --> 00:29:33,693
[SPEAKER_02]: So that's one area.

280
00:29:37,195 --> 00:29:39,437
[SPEAKER_02]: The background checks was another.

281
00:29:43,230 --> 00:29:50,312
[SPEAKER_02]: The general liability requirement is another, the size of that.

282
00:29:54,292 --> 00:30:06,754
[SPEAKER_02]: The chamber brought up a couple of points after reviewing the draft that I think it's appropriate to share with you, if they haven't already.

283
00:30:07,434 --> 00:30:10,035
[SPEAKER_02]: So I'd be happy to run through those as well, but I'll pause.

284
00:30:17,734 --> 00:30:21,098
[SPEAKER_04]: Sorry, I don't think we're if you want to know other questions at this time.

285
00:30:21,539 --> 00:30:22,200
[SPEAKER_02]: Okay, keep going.

286
00:30:22,860 --> 00:30:23,461
[SPEAKER_02]: Great.

287
00:30:25,183 --> 00:30:27,506
[SPEAKER_02]: Yep, the the Chamber of Commerce.

288
00:30:28,692 --> 00:30:34,735
[SPEAKER_02]: asked whether boards or commissions should be included in the review process.

289
00:30:37,337 --> 00:30:48,422
[SPEAKER_02]: Our thought is that the Parks Commission and Hormel are probably the two most likely to potentially have food trucks licenses in front of them.

290
00:30:49,523 --> 00:30:53,905
[SPEAKER_02]: They have events, and food trucks have attended those events in the past.

291
00:30:56,293 --> 00:31:01,815
[SPEAKER_04]: And then just for clarity, that's the thought of them weighing in on the development of this ordinance.

292
00:31:02,815 --> 00:31:04,556
[SPEAKER_02]: No, the, the approval of licenses.

293
00:31:05,696 --> 00:31:05,996
[SPEAKER_04]: Okay.

294
00:31:07,236 --> 00:31:07,456
[SPEAKER_02]: Yeah.

295
00:31:07,757 --> 00:31:08,197
[SPEAKER_04]: Yeah.

296
00:31:08,637 --> 00:31:11,918
[SPEAKER_04]: I think, um, I appreciate that comment.

297
00:31:11,978 --> 00:31:25,362
[SPEAKER_04]: I mean, just speaking, um, from the chair, I feel like that's kind of the opposite direction of the intent of this ordinance as far as just like being able to move them through at the speed of where the people need them approved, as opposed to getting them, you know, being on the schedule of,

298
00:31:26,162 --> 00:31:44,297
[SPEAKER_02]: when um you know commissions committees and so yeah and with respect to the boards and uh and the chamber we staff agrees you know it is it's difficult to to it would be difficult to add an additional kind of

299
00:31:45,300 --> 00:31:52,525
[SPEAKER_02]: you know, level of monthly approval schedules to this process.

300
00:31:52,565 --> 00:32:05,214
[SPEAKER_02]: So I think in the case of a special event in particular, the commissions would be aware of those events, we believe, and would have input.

301
00:32:05,254 --> 00:32:14,320
[SPEAKER_02]: And they may not have input on the particular truck that attends the event, but they would have input on the event schedule, et cetera.

302
00:32:17,786 --> 00:32:18,046
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you.

303
00:32:20,628 --> 00:32:36,018
[SPEAKER_02]: And then the chamber had a concern about whether the special permit process could be seen as kind of a workaround for the ordinance.

304
00:32:36,158 --> 00:32:38,160
[SPEAKER_02]: I mean, that's not our intent.

305
00:32:39,020 --> 00:32:45,444
[SPEAKER_02]: Our intent is for the Department of Health to

306
00:32:49,016 --> 00:32:52,439
[SPEAKER_02]: to administratively review and approve these.

307
00:32:53,500 --> 00:33:06,991
[SPEAKER_02]: And we think it's pretty clear in the ordinance that these one-day licenses and special event licenses are the two options, and they're pretty well-defined.

308
00:33:11,487 --> 00:33:17,049
[SPEAKER_02]: point of including a special permit option is just for very unique circumstances.

309
00:33:17,809 --> 00:33:23,972
[SPEAKER_02]: So if I could bring that language up if the board, the council would like to look at it again.

310
00:33:24,892 --> 00:33:26,813
[SPEAKER_02]: But that's our thought.

311
00:33:27,413 --> 00:33:37,797
[SPEAKER_02]: It wasn't included, was not included in the 2016 draft, but we thought it was good policy to have that in there just as an option for folks.

312
00:33:45,737 --> 00:33:46,297
[SPEAKER_04]: Councilor Collins.

313
00:33:47,638 --> 00:33:53,380
[SPEAKER_03]: Thank you President Merrill and thank you that it's great to just make sure I have an updated list of the next steps for internal review.

314
00:33:54,540 --> 00:33:58,421
[SPEAKER_03]: And I appreciate also that the chamber has been reached out to another important perspective on this.

315
00:33:59,662 --> 00:34:12,926
[SPEAKER_03]: And I'm glad to hear that the special review process is very, you know, sort of limited in circumstance so that won't it won't be an either or, you know, pick which is more convenient but rather just, you know, the appropriate process for the appropriate permit that's being sought.

316
00:34:17,569 --> 00:34:34,713
[SPEAKER_03]: I mean, I would motion to keep the paper in committee and awaiting further update from Board of Health and other city partners on these items that are still pending, unless there's other key updates or questions from my fellow councilors on this draft.

317
00:34:38,274 --> 00:34:39,975
[SPEAKER_04]: Any other discussion from the council?

318
00:34:40,275 --> 00:34:41,375
[SPEAKER_04]: So on the motion,

319
00:34:42,283 --> 00:34:50,049
[SPEAKER_04]: of Councilor Collins to keep the paper in committee until we have further updates that we're waiting on from Board of Health and some other departments, seconded by Vice Mayor Behrs.

320
00:34:50,389 --> 00:34:51,029
[SPEAKER_04]: All those in favor?

321
00:34:51,049 --> 00:34:52,751
[SPEAKER_04]: All those opposed?

322
00:34:52,791 --> 00:34:53,451
[SPEAKER_04]: Motion passes.

323
00:34:56,153 --> 00:34:57,214
[SPEAKER_04]: Any further discussion?

324
00:34:57,234 --> 00:34:58,375
[SPEAKER_04]: Anything else you'd like to add, Victor?

325
00:34:58,395 --> 00:35:00,957
[SPEAKER_02]: No, not at this time.

326
00:35:00,997 --> 00:35:04,079
[SPEAKER_02]: We really wanted to make sure we're headed in the right direction.

327
00:35:05,700 --> 00:35:06,020
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you.

328
00:35:09,713 --> 00:35:12,097
[SPEAKER_04]: Do I have a motion to adjourn?

329
00:35:13,859 --> 00:35:16,684
[SPEAKER_04]: On the motion of Councilor Sang to adjourn, seconded by Vice-Chair Behrs.

330
00:35:16,724 --> 00:35:17,324
[SPEAKER_04]: All those in favor?

331
00:35:17,345 --> 00:35:19,087
[SPEAKER_04]: All those opposed?

332
00:35:19,388 --> 00:35:20,429
[SPEAKER_04]: Motion passes, meeting adjourned.

333
00:35:21,150 --> 00:35:22,192
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you, Victor, much appreciated.

